\begin_layout Subsection
To be an intelligent citizen of the world
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of us might classically think of liberal arts education as having a
 long shelf of great books that everyone should know.
 When the great books curriculum was formed, most of human knowledge didn't
 have models in it.
 Models are a relatively new phenomena.
 When you go to college, you'll find: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Oh my gosh! I'm learning models in this course
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (whether you take anthropology to zoology, or anywhere in between).
 So, models are everywhere.
 And so in order to just be involved in a conversation, it's important these
 days that you can use and understand models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Models make us better thinkers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason models are everywhere (from anthropology to zoology) is that
 they're better.
 They sort of make us clearer, better thinkers.
 For instance, people using models to make decisions do better that people
 not using models (to make decisions) in horse race.
 So, models just make you a better thinker.
 The reason behind this is that models (sort of) weed out the logical inconsiste
ncies.
 They're analogous to a crutch.
 We humans think crazy/silly things; we can't think through all the logical
 consequences.
 Models sort of tie us to the mast (a little bit).
 And in doing so, we think better.
\end_layout

